🧾 Spring Data JPA – Key Features (SCN Format)

1. 🧠 Concept
Spring Data JPA is a layer on top of JPA that reduces boilerplate code by providing ready-made repository implementations and intelligent query handling.

2. ⚙️ Core Features
🔹 1. Repository Abstraction
No need to write DAO layer manually
Just create interface:
public interface UserRepository extends JpaRepository<User, Long> {}


🔹 2. Built-in CRUD Methods
Ready-to-use methods:
save()
findById()
findAll()
deleteById()

🔹 3. Query Method Naming (Auto Query Generation)
Queries generated from method names:
List<User> findByName(String name);
List<User> findByAgeGreaterThan(int age);


🔹 4. Pagination & Sorting
Built-in support:
Page<User> findAll(Pageable pageable);


🔹 5. Custom Queries (@Query)
Write JPQL or native SQL:
@Query("SELECT u FROM User u WHERE u.email = :email")
User findByEmail(String email);


🔹 6. JPA Integration
Works with JPA providers like Hibernate
Handles EntityManager internally

🔹 7. Transaction Management
Integrated with Spring’s @Transactional
Ensures ACID properties

🔹 8. Auditing Support
Tracks changes automatically:
Created Date
Last Modified Date
@CreatedDate
@LastModifiedDate


🔹 9. Derived Delete & Update Queries
void deleteByName(String name);


🔹 10. Projection Support
Fetch only required fields:
interface UserNameOnly {
    String getName();
}


3. 🚀 Approach (How It Works)
Define Entity
Create Repository Interface
Extend JpaRepository
Inject and use in Service
Spring auto-generates implementation

4. 💻 Code Example
public interface ProductRepository extends JpaRepository<Product, Long> {
    List<Product> findByTitle(String title);
}

@Autowired
private ProductRepository repo;

repo.save(new Product());
repo.findByTitle("Phone");


5. 🎯 Key Points
Eliminates boilerplate DAO code
Auto query generation
Powerful abstraction over JPA
Supports pagination & sorting
Integrates seamlessly with Spring

6. 📌 Learnings
Focus on method naming rules (very important for interviews)
Use custom queries when logic becomes complex
Best used with Hibernate + Spring Boot


🧾 Spring Data JPA – Rules for Auto Query Generation (Derived Queries)

1. 🧠 Concept
Auto Query Generation (Derived Queries) lets Spring Data JPA create queries from method names—no @Query needed.
👉 Example:
List<User> findByName(String name);

➡ Automatically generates query behind the scenes.

2. ⚙️ Core Rules

🔹 1. Method Must Start with Keywords
Common prefixes:
Keyword
Purpose
findBy
Fetch data
readBy
Same as find
getBy
Same as find
countBy
Count records
existsBy
Check existence
deleteBy
Delete records


🔹 2. Use Entity Field Names (NOT Column Names)
❌ Wrong:
findByUser_name(String name);

✅ Correct:
findByName(String name);


🔹 3. Follow CamelCase Naming
Field names must match exactly:
findByFirstName(String firstName);


🔹 4. Combine Conditions Using Keywords
Keyword
Meaning
And
AND condition
Or
OR condition

findByNameAndAge(String name, int age);
findByNameOrEmail(String name, String email);


🔹 5. Use Comparison Keywords
Keyword
Example
GreaterThan
findByAgeGreaterThan(int age)
LessThan
findByPriceLessThan(double price)
Between
findByAgeBetween(int a, int b)


🔹 6. Pattern Matching Keywords
Keyword
Example
Like
findByNameLike(String name)
Containing
findByNameContaining(String name)
StartingWith
findByNameStartingWith(String prefix)
EndingWith
findByNameEndingWith(String suffix)


🔹 7. Null & Boolean Handling
findByEmailIsNull();
findByActiveTrue();
findByActiveFalse();


🔹 8. Sorting Support
findByNameOrderByAgeAsc(String name);
findByNameOrderByAgeDesc(String name);


🔹 9. Nested Property Traversal
Works with relationships:
findByDepartmentName(String deptName);


🔹 10. Return Types Supported
Type
Usage
List<T>
Multiple results
Optional<T>
Single result
Page<T>
Pagination
long
Count


3. 🚀 Approach
Start with keyword (findBy)
Add field name (exact match)
Add condition (And, GreaterThan, etc.)
Match parameters with fields
Choose correct return type

4. 💻 Examples
List<Product> findByTitle(String title);

List<Product> findByPriceGreaterThan(double price);

List<Product> findByTitleAndPrice(String title, double price);

boolean existsBySku(String sku);

long countByCategory(String category);


5. 🎯 Key Points
No SQL required
Based on method naming convention
Uses entity fields only
Supports conditions, sorting, pagination
Best for simple queries

6. 📌 Learnings
Naming must be exact & precise
Long method names = complex logic → use @Query instead
Most used in real apps for quick CRUD + filtering



